|url=http://www.londondogforum.co.uk/the-british-bulldog-c428.html|accessdate=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811210701/http://www.londondogforum.co.uk/the-british-bulldog-c428.html|archive-date=2014-08-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Red kite]] ''([[Wales]])'' ||''Milvus milvus'' ||[[File:Milvus milvus R(ThKraft).jpg|150px]] ||<ref name=\"visitwalesNatSym\">{{cite web|title=National symbols of Wales|url=http://www.visitwales.com/explore/traditions-history/national-symbols|website=visitwales.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Unicorn]] ''([[Scotland]])'' ||style=\"background:#ccc;\"|'''Mythical''' ||[[File:Oftheunicorn.jpg|150px]] ||<ref name=\"globalpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Lifestyle/national-animals-legendary-extinct-imaginary/story?id=20170452#2 |title=National Animals: The Legendary, Extinct and Imaginary-2 of 9 |publisher=abcnews.go.com |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/heritage/scottish-fact-of-the-week-scotland-s-official-animal-the-unicorn-1-2564399 |title=Scottish fact of the week: Scotland's official animal, the Unicorn |publisher=scotsman.com |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish-at-heart.com/unicorn-of-scotland.html |title=The Mystical Unicorn Of Scotland |publisher=scottish-at-heart.com |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://unrealfacts.com/scotlands-national-animal-is-a-unicorn/ |title=Scotland's National Animal Is A Unicorn |publisher=sunrealfacts.com |accessdate=2014-10-03|date=4 April 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Y Ddraig Goch]] ''(The Red Dragon [[Wales]])'' ||style=\"background:#ccc;\"|'''Mythical''' ||[[File:Flag of Wales 2.svg|150px]] ||<ref name=visitwalesNatSym /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Lifestyle/national-animals-legendary-extinct-imaginary/story?id=20170452#2 |title=National Animals: The Legendary, Extinct and Imaginary-7 of 9 |publisher=abcnews.go.com |accessdate=2014-10-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{USA}} || [[Bald eagle]] ''(national bird)''||''Haliaeetus leucocephalus'' ||[[File:Haliaeetus leucocephalus.jpeg|150px]] ||<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Lawrence |first1=E.A. |year=1990 |title=Symbol of a Nation: The Bald Eagle in American Culture |journal=The Journal of American Culture |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=63\u201369 |doi=10.1111/j.1542-734X.1990.1301_63.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Symbols of U.S. Government: The Bald Eagle |work=Ben's Guide to U.S. Government For Kids |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |accessdate=12 April 2016|url=http://www.rightsofthepeople.com/education/government_for_kids/3-5/symbols/eagle.php}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[American bison]] ''(national mammal)''||''Bison bison'' ||[[File:American bison k5680-1.jpg|150px]] ||<ref>[https://www.worldwildlife.org/stories/a-symbol-of-hope-us-government-designates-bison-as-the-national-mammal A symbol of hope: US government designates bison as the national mammal]</ref><ref>[http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/north-american-bison-national-mammal-us-222975 Obama Makes North American Bison National Mammal]</ref>\n|-\n|{{VEN}}<!--Venezuela--> || [[Venezuelan troupial]] ''(national bird)''|| ''Icterus icterus'' || [[File:Curacao-Icterus-Icterus-2013.JPG|150px]] ||<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.minci.gob.ve/efemerides-el-turpial-es-declarado-ave-nacional-en-1958 |title = EFEM\u00c9RIDES &#124; el Turpial es declarado Ave Nacional en 1958|date = 23 May 2018}}</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160525164420/http://www.vtv.gob.ve/articulos/2016/05/23/23-de-mayo-declaracion-de-la-orquidea-y-el-turpial-como-simbolos-nacionales-4035.html</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{flag|Zimbabwe}} || [[Sable antelope]] ''(national animal)'' || ''Hippotragus niger'' || [[File:Sable antelope (Hippotragus niger) adult male.jpg|150px]] || <ref name=\"Zimbabwe\">{{cite web |title=Zimbabwe State Symbols, Songs, Flags, and More |url=https://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/africa/zimbabwe/zwsymbols.htm |website=Worldatlas.com |accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[African fish eagle]] ''(national bird)'' || ''Haliaeetus vocifer'' || [[File:African Fish Eagle AdF.jpg|150px]] || <ref name=\"Zimbabwe\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Animals|Lists}}\n* [[State animal]]\n* [[List of national birds]]\n* [[Animals as heraldic charges]]\n* [[Floral emblem]]\n* [[National personification]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{National symbols}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of National Animals}}\n[[Category:Lists of national symbols|Animal]]\n[[Category:Lists of animals]]\n", "name_user": "Dcr21", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNational animals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_national_animals"}
{"title_page": "Media coverage of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{For|broader discussion of the pandemic's impact on the journalism industry|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on journalism}}\n'''Media coverage of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' has varied by country, time period and media outlet, ranging from outright censorship to extensive coverage.\n\n==Level of coverage==\nWithin January 2020, the first full month in which the outbreak was known, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' recorded 41,000 English-language articles containing the term \"coronavirus\", of which 19,000 made it to headlines. This was compared with the [[Kivu Ebola epidemic]], which had 1,800 articles and 700 headlines in August 2018. [[Paul Levinson]], a researcher in communications and media studies, attributed this wide disparity to backlash from perceived overcoverage of the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|2014 Ebola outbreak]], coupled with concerns regarding Chinese censorship of the coverage.<ref>{{cite news|title=How News Coverage of Coronavirus in 2020 Compares to Ebola in 2018 |url=https://time.com/5779872/coronavirus-ebola-news-coverage |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n''[[Recode]]'' reported on 17 March that, out of 3,000 high-traffic news sites, around 1 percent of published articles are related to the disease, but those articles generate around 13 percent of all views, with subtopics such as [[social distancing]], [[flattening the curve]] and [[self-quarantine]] being particularly popular. The total number of article views itself was some 30 percent higher in mid-March of 2020 compared to in mid-March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Molla |first1=Rani |title=It\u2019s not just you. Everybody is reading the news more because of coronavirus. |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/17/21182770/news-consumption-coronavirus-traffic-views |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[Recode]] |agency=[[Vox Media]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==By country==\n===China===\n{{further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China}}\nThe Chinese government has received significant criticism for its censoring of the extent of the outbreak. Immediately following the initial [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|quarantine of Wuhan and nearby cities]], Chinese state media such as the ''[[People's Daily]]'' initially encouraged social media posts seeking help between citizens on platforms such as [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How the Coronavirus Outbreak Played out on China's Social Media |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/how-the-coronavirus-outbreak-played-out-on-chinas-social-media |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The Diplomat]] |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> Multiple journalists then published investigative pieces contradicting official statements and media, indicating that the number of cases in Wuhan is significantly larger than is reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Critics Say China Has Suppressed And Censored Information In Coronavirus Outbreak |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/08/803766743/critics-say-china-has-suppressed-and-censored-information-in-coronavirus-outbrea |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=8 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nIn reporting about the outbreak, British tabloid newspapers such as ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Daily Mail]]'' used language described as \"fear-inducing\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: how media coverage of epidemics often stokes fear and panic |url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-how-media-coverage-of-epidemics-often-stokes-fear-and-panic-131844 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |date=14 February 2020}}</ref> According to [[Edelman (firm)|Edelman]]'s Trust Barometer, journalists were the least-trusted source for information regarding the pandemic in the UK, with 43 percent out of the surveyed trusting them to report the truth, behind government officials (48%) and \"most-affected countries\" (46%). This was despite conventional media being the primary source of information regarding the pandemic in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tobitt |first1=Charlotte |title=Coronavirus: Public distrust journalists despite relying on news media for daily updates, survey shows |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/coronavirus-public-distrust-journalists-despite-relying-on-news-media-for-daily-updates-survey-shows |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Press Gazette]]|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\nOpinion hosts and guests on [[Fox News]], a conservative media outlet, initially downplayed the disease outbreak, with some guests accusing other media outlets of overplaying the disease for political reasons.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=David |title=Fox News accused of downplaying coronavirus as it moves to protect staff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/mar/13/fox-news-accused-of-downplaying-coronavirus-as-it-moves-to-protect-staff |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> One [[Fox Business]] host, [[Trish Regan]], claimed on her show ''Trish Regan Primetime'' that coronavirus' media coverage was deliberately created by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] as a \"mass hysteria to encourage a market sell-off\". On the other hand, [[Tucker Carlson]] took a much more serious position regarding the disease, criticizing other hosts which compared it with ordinary [[Flu season|seasonal]] [[Influenza|flu]].  Regan's show was later suspended.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gabbatt |first1=Adam |title='We have a responsibility': Fox News declares coronavirus a crisis in abrupt U-turn |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/mar/17/fox-news-coronavirus-outbreak-trump |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Donald Trump]] initially accused media outlets such as [[CNN]] of \"doing everything they can to instill fear in people\", a statement echoed by Acting White House Chief of Staff [[Mick Mulvaney]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karni |first1=Annie |title=Trump Criticizes Media for Coverage of Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/us/politics/cpac-coronavirus.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> Trump had been mentioned in between a quarter and a third of media reports regarding the virus in the US between 25 February and 28 February.<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Coverage and Coronavirus Panic: What the Numbers Show|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2020/03/02/media_coverage_and_coronavirus_panic_what_the_numbers_show_142539.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[RealClearPolitics]] |date=2 March 2020}}</ref>  An [[Axios]] survey, conducted between 5 and 9 March 2020, found that 62% of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] supporters believed that the outbreak's coverage by media is exaggerated, compared to 31% of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] supporters and 35% of independents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republicans are twice as likely as Democrats to view coronavirus coverage as exaggerated |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-poll-republicans-democrats-news-coverage-e092414b-b1ca-40ad-9293-eeb322b2fb3e.html |publisher=[[Axios]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on journalism]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on social media]]\n* [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Media coverage and representation|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|broader discussion of the pandemic's impact on the journalism industry|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on journalism}}\n'''Media coverage of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' has varied by country, time period and media outlet, ranging from outright censorship to extensive coverage.\n\n==Level of coverage==\nWithin January 2020, the first full month in which the outbreak was known, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' recorded 41,000 English-language articles containing the term \"coronavirus\", of which 19,000 made it to headlines. This was compared with the [[Kivu Ebola epidemic]], which had 1,800 articles and 700 headlines in August 2018. [[Paul Levinson]], a researcher in communications and media studies, attributed this wide disparity to backlash from perceived overcoverage of the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|2014 Ebola outbreak]], coupled with concerns regarding Chinese censorship of the coverage.<ref>{{cite news|title=How News Coverage of Coronavirus in 2020 Compares to Ebola in 2018 |url=https://time.com/5779872/coronavirus-ebola-news-coverage |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n''[[Recode]]'' reported on 17 March that, out of 3,000 high-traffic news sites, around 1 percent of published articles are related to the disease, but those articles generate around 13 percent of all views, with subtopics such as [[social distancing]], [[flattening the curve]] and [[self-quarantine]] being particularly popular. The total number of article views itself was some 30 percent higher in mid-March of 2020 compared to in mid-March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Molla |first1=Rani |title=It\u2019s not just you. Everybody is reading the news more because of coronavirus. |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/17/21182770/news-consumption-coronavirus-traffic-views |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[Recode]] |agency=[[Vox Media]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==By country==\n===China===\n{{further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China}}\nThe Chinese government has received significant criticism for its censoring of the extent of the outbreak. Immediately following the initial [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|quarantine of Wuhan and nearby cities]], Chinese state media such as the ''[[People's Daily]]'' initially encouraged social media posts seeking help between citizens on platforms such as [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How the Coronavirus Outbreak Played out on China's Social Media |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/how-the-coronavirus-outbreak-played-out-on-chinas-social-media |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The Diplomat]] |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> Multiple journalists then published investigative pieces contradicting official statements and media, indicating that the number of cases in Wuhan is significantly larger than is reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Critics Say China Has Suppressed And Censored Information In Coronavirus Outbreak |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/08/803766743/critics-say-china-has-suppressed-and-censored-information-in-coronavirus-outbrea |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=8 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nIn reporting about the outbreak, British tabloid newspapers such as ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Daily Mail]]'' used language described as \"fear-inducing\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: how media coverage of epidemics often stokes fear and panic |url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-how-media-coverage-of-epidemics-often-stokes-fear-and-panic-131844 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |date=14 February 2020}}</ref> According to [[Edelman (firm)|Edelman]]'s Trust Barometer, journalists were the least-trusted source for information regarding the pandemic in the UK, with 43 percent out of the surveyed trusting them to report the truth, behind government officials (48%) and \"most-affected countries\" (46%). This was despite conventional media being the primary source of information regarding the pandemic in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tobitt |first1=Charlotte |title=Coronavirus: Public distrust journalists despite relying on news media for daily updates, survey shows |url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/coronavirus-public-distrust-journalists-despite-relying-on-news-media-for-daily-updates-survey-shows |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Press Gazette]]|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\nOpinion hosts and guests on [[Fox News]], a conservative media outlet, initially downplayed the disease outbreak, with some guests accusing other media outlets of overplaying the disease for political reasons.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=David |title=Fox News accused of downplaying coronavirus as it moves to protect staff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/mar/13/fox-news-accused-of-downplaying-coronavirus-as-it-moves-to-protect-staff |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> One [[Fox Business]] host, [[Trish Regan]], claimed on her show ''Trish Regan Primetime'' that coronavirus' media coverage was deliberately created by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] as a \"mass hysteria to encourage a market sell-off\". On the other hand, [[Tucker Carlson]] took a much more serious position regarding the disease, criticizing other hosts which compared it with ordinary [[Flu season|seasonal]] [[Influenza|flu]].  Regan's show was later suspended.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gabbatt |first1=Adam |title='We have a responsibility': Fox News declares coronavirus a crisis in abrupt U-turn |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/mar/17/fox-news-coronavirus-outbreak-trump |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Donald Trump]] initially accused media outlets such as [[CNN]] of \"doing everything they can to instill fear in people\", a statement echoed by Acting White House Chief of Staff [[Mick Mulvaney]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karni |first1=Annie |title=Trump Criticizes Media for Coverage of Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/us/politics/cpac-coronavirus.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> Trump had been mentioned in between a quarter and a third of media reports regarding the virus in the US between 25 February and 28 February.<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Coverage and Coronavirus Panic: What the Numbers Show|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2020/03/02/media_coverage_and_coronavirus_panic_what_the_numbers_show_142539.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[RealClearPolitics]] |date=2 March 2020}}</ref>  An [[Axios]] survey, conducted between 5 and 9 March 2020, found that 62% of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] supporters believed that the outbreak's coverage by media is exaggerated, compared to 31% of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] supporters and 35% of independents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republicans are twice as likely as Democrats to view coronavirus coverage as exaggerated |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-poll-republicans-democrats-news-coverage-e092414b-b1ca-40ad-9293-eeb322b2fb3e.html |publisher=[[Axios]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on journalism]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on social media]]\n* [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Media coverage and representation|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Sdkb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_coverage_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Manuel Gamio", "text_new": "[[Image:Manuel Gamio.jpg|thumb|right|Manuel Gamio]]\n'''Manuel Gamio''' (1883\u20131960) was a Mexican [[Anthropology|anthropologist]], [[Archaeology|archaeologist]], [[Sociology|sociologist]], and a leader of the ''[[indigenismo]]'' movement. Although he rejected full sovereignty for indigenous communities in Mexico, he argued that their self-governing organizations, such as tribal governments, municipal organizations, and elected community leaders should be recognized and respected.<ref name=\"Gamio1942\" /> He is often considered as the father of modern anthropological studies in [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"Galliard2004\" /> He devised a well-known system for classifying the [[hunter-gatherer]]s of Central America.\n\n==Education==\nGamio was born in [[Mexico City]], where he studied engineering at the School of Mining. However, at age 19 he left his studies to work on a family rubber plantation, where the states of [[Oaxaca]], [[Veracruz]] and [[Puebla]] join. There he learned [[Nahuatl]] from the plantation workers and developed a strong interest in [[indigenous peoples of Mexico|Mexico's indigenous cultures]].<ref name=\"Galliard2004\" />\n\nHe returned to study at the National Museum under [[Z\u00e9lia Nuttall]], who in 1909 sent him to study under [[Franz Boas]] at [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"Galliard2004\" /> There he earned a Ph.D. From Boas he adopted the cultural approach characteristic of the anthropology of the United States in the twentieth century.<ref name=\"Darnell2001\" /> Boas considered Gamio one of his best students.\n\n==Work in Mexico and Guatemala==\n[[File:Templo Mayor 2015 126.jpg|thumb|right|Statue at Templo Mayor, Mexico City]]\nHe returned to Mexico in 1910 and the following year he was among the founders of the [[International School of American Archeology and Ethnology in Mexico|Escuela Internacional de Arqueolog\u00eda y Etnolog\u00eda Americana (International School of Archaeology and Ethnology of the Americas)]] in Mexico City, with funds obtained from Germany and the United States. Other individuals associated with the school included [[Eduard Seler]], [[Alfred M. Tozzer]] and Boas. This was during the [[Mexican Revolution]], and thus was a difficult time to establish new scientific institutions. Gamio was director of the school from 1916 through 1920, when it closed for lack of funds.\n\nIn 1911 he established a ceramic sequence for the [[Valley of Mexico]] based on earlier stratigraphic excavations at [[Azcapotzalco]], [[Mexican Federal District|Distrito Federal]]. Between 1913 and 1916 he was inspector general of archaeological monuments of the [[Secretar\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica|Mexican Ministry of Public Education]]. He performed field work at various places in the Valley of Mexico, including [[Copilco]], [[Cuicuilco]] and the [[Templo Mayor]] (all in the Distrito Federal); Chalchihuites, Zacatecas; [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]]; [[Ecuador]] and Miraflores, Guatemala.\n\nHe was the first scientific investigator to explore [[Teotihuacan]]. A result of these investigations was the book ''La poblaci\u00f3n del valle de Teotihuacan'' (The Population of the Valley of Teotihuacan), published in 1922. A revision of his Columbia thesis, this work is still an important source for ethnographic information on the northern zone of the [[Mexico (state)|State of Mexico]]. He also produced some documentary films. He estimated the maximum population of Teotihuacan at 300,000.<ref name=\"Goliath\" /> He criticized the Mexican census for classifying Spanish-speaking Indians as whites and those married by traditional rites as single.\n\nEarlier, in 1916, he had published the important book ''Forjando patria: pro nacionalismo'' (Mexico City: Libreria de Porr\u00faa Hermanos) (Forging a Fatherland), a treatise on [[cultural assimilation]] of indigenous Mexicans into the racially mixed society of the country. Other works in Spanish include ''Hacia un M\u00e9xico nuevo'' (1935) and ''Consideraciones sobre el problema del indigenismo'' (1948).\n\nIn the 1920s he investigated the highlands of [[Guatemala]], near the cities of [[Quiche]], [[Huehuetenango]] and [[Quetzaltenango]], concentrating on pottery styles. Due to the similarity of pottery from Guatemala and central Mexico, Gamio believed the latter area to be the original source of Mayan civilization. He hypothesized that some of the early natives of central Mexico abandoned that area in search of a place free of earthquakes and volcanos.<ref name=\"ScienceNews\" />\n\nGamio's publications on Mexico's indigenous was important for \"reinstating [[Anahuac (Aztec)|Anahuac]] as the glorious foundation of Mexican history and culture.\"<ref name=\"Brading\" /> Gamio was one among many, including President [[L\u00e1zaro C\u00e1rdenas]] in the 1930s, who worked for the integration of the indigenous into national life.<ref name=\"Lacy\" />\n\n==Work in the United States==\nIn 1925 he emigrated to the United States after denouncing corruption in the Mexican Ministry of Education. He concentrated on the subjects of migration and labor involving Mexicans in the United States, for the [[Social Science Research Council]] in Washington, D.C. Gamio published two books on this research \u2013  ''Mexican Immigration to the United States'' (1930) and ''The Mexican Immigrant: His Life Story'' (1931) \u2013 this time in English. These books have only recently been translated into Spanish for the use of present-day Mexican anthropologists and sociologists.<ref name=\"Review\" />\n\nHe returned to Mexico in 1930, where he held various government positions, conducted sociological and applied anthropological investigations, and directed the [[Inter-American Indian Institute]] from its foundation in 1942 until his death in 1960.<ref name=\"Galliard2004\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Gamio1942\">{{cite journal | last=Gamio | first= Manuel |date=October 1942 | title=Calificacion de Caracteristicas Culturales de los Grupos Indigenas | journal=America Indigena | location=Mexico, DF: Instituto Indigenista Interamericano | volume=4 | issue=2 | pages=17\u201322}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ScienceNews\">{{cite news | url=http://www.sciencenews.org/pages/sn_arch/9_21_96/timeline.htm | title=Ancient Mayas Studied Earthquakes; Sought Land Free From Them for Home | publisher=The Science News-Letter | date=18 September 1926}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Brading\">{{cite journal | author=[[David Brading|D.A. Brading]] | title=Manuel Gamio and Official Indigenism in Mexico | journal=[[Bulletin of Latin American Research]] | volume=7 | year=1988 | pages=76}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lacy\">Elaine C. Lacy, \"The 1921 Centennial Celebration of Mexico's Independence: State Building and Popular Negotiation\" in William H. Beezley and David Lorey, eds., ''!Viva Mexico!!Viva la Independencia!: Celebrations of September 16''. Wilmington DL: Scholarly Resources 2001, pp. 215\u2013216.</ref>\n<ref name=\"Review\">[https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/151/15102108.pdf Review of ''El inmigrante mexicano: la historia de su vida: Entrevistas completas, 1926\u201327''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709183123/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/151/15102108.pdf |date=2011-07-09 }}, ''Migraciones Internacionales'', vol. 2, no. 1, Jan.\u2013June 2003, pp. 171\u2013175</ref>\n<ref name=\"Darnell2001\">{{cite book | author=Darnell, Regna | authorlink=Regna Darnell | year=2001 | title=Invisible Genealogies: A History of Americanist Anthropology |series=Critical studies in the history of anthropology series | volume=1 | location=Lincoln | publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]] | isbn=0-8032-1710-2 | oclc=44502297 | pages=323}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Goliath\">{{cite web | url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0199-193972_ITM | title=Un siglo de \u00e9xitos de la arqueolog\u00eda mexicana}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Galliard2004\">{{cite book | author=Gaillard, G\u00e9rald | year=2004 | title=The Routledge Dictionary of Anthropologists | edition=English translation of ''Dictionnaire des ethnologues et des anthropologues'' (1997) | others=Peter James Bowman (trans.) | location=London and New York | publisher=[[Routledge]] | isbn=0-415-22825-5 | oclc=52288643 | pages=255\u2013257}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{commons category|Manuel Gamio}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Le\u00f3n-Portilla|first=Miguel|title=Manuel Gamio, 1883\u20131960|journal=American Anthropologist| volume = 64 |pages=356\u2013366|date=1962|url=https://anthrosource.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1525/aa.1962.64.2.02a00110|doi=10.1525/aa.1962.64.2.02a00110}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gamio, Manuel}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mexican anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Mexican archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Mexican sociologists]]\n[[Category:Mexican Mesoamericanists]]\n[[Category:Mesoamerican archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Mesoamerican anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Aztec scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mesoamericanists]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Manuel Gamio.jpg|thumb|right|Manuel Gamio]]\n'''Manuel Gamio''' (1883\u20131960) was a Mexican [[Anthropology|anthropologist]], [[Archaeology|archaeologist]], [[Sociology|sociologist]], and a leader of the ''[[indigenismo]]'' movement. Although he rejected full sovereignty for indigenous communities in Mexico, he argued that their self-governing organizations, such as tribal governments, municipal organizations, and elected community leaders should be recognized and respected.<ref name=\"Gamio1942\" /> He is often considered as the father of modern anthropological studies in [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"Galliard2004\" /> He devised a well-known system for classifying the [[hunter-gatherer]]s of Central America.\n\n==Education==\nGamio was born in [[Mexico City]], where he studied engineering at the School of Mining. However, at age 19 he left his studies to work on